        <ontology:hasEntity rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/resource/Q8425"/>
        <ontology:hasEntity rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/resource/Q959362"/>
        <ontology:isPresentedBefore rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N54_VC_26_UK/event/ev11"/>
        <ontology:is_identified_by rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/appellation/Innovation"/>
        <ontology:partOfNarrative rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N54_VC_26_UK"/>
        <ontology:took_place_at rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/phenomenal_place/52.833333333_-3.916666666"/>
        <ontology:took_place_at rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/place/0"/>
        <ontology:hasDescription>The type of innovation of this VC (Value Chain) is Endogenous and Exogenous. Gin as a product is not new, however the processing of gin in upland areas such as Gwynedd is new and innovative. There has also been a massive increase in gin production across the UK recent years, i.e. within whisky distilleries and to meet the growing demand of local and flavoured gins (and increased demand from younger generation as gin is now considered a &amp;apos;trendy&amp;apos; drink). The innovation is related to New products, New processes, New marketing strategies and New governance systems. The land use systems involved are Forestry, Natural land and upland water. The local assets include Natural, social and cultural.  </ontology:hasDescription>
    </NamedIndividual>
    


    <!-- https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N54_VC_26_UK/event/ev11 -->


    <NamedIndividual rdf:about="https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N54_VC_26_UK/event/ev11">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/event-type/valorisation_event"/>
